t soon).©˘ĄĽWrap_OnľÝŰŁ8 11 64 12¨You use the RETURN key when you want to end a line and goto the beginning of the next one.  If you press it again,you leave a blank line, and you can start typing on thenext line.You're about to start a new paragraph.  To put a blank linebetween paragraphs,                          Press RETURN twice.©˘ĄĄĽWrap_OffľÝŰŁ15 15 42 6¨The cursor drops down two lines.We'll type the next paragraph for you.©˘ĄĽTypeWrapľĽWrap_OffľÝŰŁ9 14 62 10¨When you pressed RETURN twice, the cursor moved downtwo lines.And when we began to type the next paragraph, we didn'tneed to press RETURN again, because the words "profitable"and "payroll" wrapped around, along the way.©˘ĄÝŰŁ8 6 65 13¨Suddenly you get a call that the meringue's getting toosticky to spread.  You've got to do something quickly.You want to save what you've written--that is, put a copyon your disk--so you won't lose it if someone comes by andplays with the keys while you're away from the desk.  Here'sthe quick way to save a document on a disk.        Hold down OPEN APPLE and press S for save.©˘ŔSĽOA_SaveľÝŰŁ9 7 62 10¨Presto!  Your document's been stored on the disk, underthe name Loan Letter.  (AppleWorks leaves a copy of yourdocument on the screen, so that you could go on workingon it, if you wanted.)Now you can go check out the meringue.©˘ĄĽCLEARSCREENľÝŰŁ9 7 58 8¨You've started a letter from scratch, and saved it onyour disk.  In the next lesson, you'll see how you canbring a file in from the disk onto your Desktop, andwork on it.©˘ĄÝŰŁ5 8 70 11¨                        What Next?To go on to the next lesson, on Getting a File and Editing, pressRETURN.To return to the Word Processor Lesson Menu, hold down OPEN APPLEand press ESC.©˘ĄÝŰSEC2Ł8 6 58 12¨          2.  Getting a File and EditingWell, now, you've taken care of the lemon meringuecrisis, and half a dozen other emergencies, includinga blown fuse that shut down power in the entire plant.Alas, when the power went out, the computer forgotthe text of your letter.  Its memory went dead.©˘ĄÝŰŁ2 6 74 8¨In this lesson, we'll show you how to get your file back from the diskto the Desktop, so you can edit your letter.  The disk is like aphonograph record--it doesn't forget, although it can be scratched.©˘ĄĽMainMenuľÝŰŁ3 14 74 10¨After the head chef put a new fuse in, and the lights came on, youstarted AppleWorks again.  Now you're looking at the Main Menu.Since the option to "Add files to the Desktop" is already highlighted,                              Press RETURN.©˘ĄĽAddMenuľÝŰŁ45 0 35 14¨Now AppleWorks wants toknow where your file is.You saved yours by puttingit on the disk, so choose toget a file from the "currentdisk."  Since that option'salready highlighted, all youhave to do is         Press RETURN.©˘ĄĽAddFilesľÝŰŁ53 0 27 8¨AppleWorks goes outto the disk, anddiscovers what filesyou have there.©˘ĄÝŰŁ53 0 27 11¨AppleWorks arrangesthis list of files bytype (Word Processor,Data Base, Spread-sheet), thenalphabetically withineach type.©˘ĄÝŰŁ20 0 60 9¨There's the file you want:  Loan Letter.  You can tellAppleWorks to get that one by highlighting it.        Use the DOWN ARROW to select Loan Letter,                   then press RETURN.©˘ÄĄĽGet_FileľĽWrap_OffľÝŰŁ22 13 36 6¨And just like that, you see thefile appear in front of you.©˘ĄÝŰŁ12 14 58 7¨You've recovered from the lemon meringue crisis,and added a file to the Desktop.  Your letter wasout on the disk waiting for you to return.©˘ĄÝŰSEC3Ł7 12 66 9¨               3.  Moving Phrases AroundNow that you have your loan letter back on the Desktop, youcan move around in it, and insert, replace, and deleteinformation--without having to retype the whole letter.©˘ĄÝŰŁ8 11 60 7¨As you look over the letter, you notice some mistakes,and some places you'd like to tidy up.  You're going toclean up the first draft.©˘ĄĽWrap_OnľÝŰŁ8 12 60 11¨First, there's no "t" in "budget," near the end of thefirst paragraph.  (It's our fault; we did the typing).Your cursor is on the first character in the letter.Here's how to move down to "budge."                   Press the DOWN arrow        until you're on the line with the mistake.©˘ÄÄÄÄÝŰŁ0 11 75 12¨Now you could move to the right, one character at a time, with theRIGHT ARROW key.  But there's a faster way.You can jump whole words at a time.  Here's how to leap over 7 words:                      Hold down the OPEN APPLE key   and press the RIGHT ARROW enough times to reach the word "budge".©˘ŔŇŔŇŔŇŔŇŔŇŔŇŔŇĽWrap_OffľÝŰŁ8 14 62 8¨You did it!  OPEN APPLE speeds up the arrow keys,making the cursor jump a whole word at each keystroke.You're ready to make that correction now.©˘ĄĽWrap_OnľÝŰŁ11 14 44 9¨Your cursor is on the "b" in "budge."Now we need to move to the trouble spot.         Press the RIGHT ARROW    until the cursor is on the comma.©˘ŇŇŇŇŇÝŰŁ14 14 52 7¨All you have to do to insert a letter is type.               Type   t©˘tĽWrap_OffľÝŰŁ8 14 64 9¨Let's say you reread the sentence, and decide it willsound better if you write "budget, and prospects."You don't want to keep the "our" in there, so you're goingto replace it with "and"--the same number of characters.©˘ĄĽWrap_OnľÝŰŁ8 10 64 9¨AppleWorks allows you to replace characters instead ofdeleting, then inserting.  But you need a different cursor,the strikeover cursor.  To get the strikeover cursor,  Hold down OPEN APPLE and press E (to exchange cursors).©˘ŔEÝŰŁ8 10 62 12¨You've changed the cursor into a solid rectangle, sofrom now on, whatever you type replaces what was therebefore.  The cursor's on the comma, but you want to leavethe comma there.To skip ahead, without replacing anything:                 Press the RIGHT ARROW twice.©˘ŇŇÝŰŁ25 15 40 